column68: 3/27- reconnecting with Fabius after he gets back from his sabbatical.
column71:
Sources
-Typeform
-Salesforce (reps ask customers how happy they are)
-Intercom (he wasn’t initially thinking of this as a feedback source but is interested in seeing what we can surface from support data)

Volume 
-15k to 30k survey responses annually (would like ballpark pricing)

-Capturing feedback in an unstructured way through multiple places
-Using typeform but response rate is lower than he would like
-Want to increase the amount of customer feedback that we generate, bring all the feedback that we recieve on a unified measurement system and bring into a tool that allows to uncover the biggest satisfaction drivers

What decisions are you trying to make?
-want to understand at a large scale what drives satisfaction in our users
-want to leverage feedback more implicitly (for context, heyjobs is a job matching marketplace that matches employers with talent in their platform, but another part of their offering is that employers provide hey jobs with a marketing budget that they distribute across various channels to attract talent, so they want to feedback inform the logic behind how they marketing budget is distributed)


What’s the biggest challenge?
-Not actionable, feedback is silod, want to get a common ground
-feedback isn’t being used at all


-They’re sending surveys that ask customers to rank their satisfaction on a scale of 1 to 5, then provide an reason why those that score in an open-text field - wants to use Enterpret to create a report where he can see the reasons provided for each score

-one of the problems they’re having with typeform is that it only captures full responses, so if you don’t complete the form, you lose the whole response, so they’re looking at a tool that does both surveying as well as an analysis of the open-text data

1/18- Decent call with Fabius. Have about 15k survey responses a year, which is the V1 use case for them.

Some things that concern me:
Partnering with the CMO on this - no budget yet exists. They will be the exectuive sponsor.

Mentioned a few other solutions they're looking at today: Lumoa, InMoment, 

Talked about ease of use being a key use case. Point blank said "this may be a bit too advanced for what we need today"

I asked if depth of insights is even something important to them right now. He said not necessarily, but they will need to get there one day. 

Vocalized high level pricing, going to have a few other vendor chats this week, then connect next week to see what makes sense as the next steps from here.

Still figuring out what survey solution will be best, wants a solution that can do surveys as well.

Wants to decide on a solution in the next 2-4 weeks. Then summary, share with CMO, and make a decision.

1/29- Met with Fabius. Said they have already eliminated another vendor, and it is now just us and InMoment. Final thing is they would like to test this on their survey data.

Pushed on this a bit, tried to steer towards intercom. Send surveys via intercom today that are hosted on Sprig, but the tickets are not a core use case for the sake of this proof of concept. Really wants to see how we work on their open text feedback.

Asked about how his surveys are constructed today, and will get examples before we discuss a PoV.

Fabius is going to be OOO for a MONTH after Friday. Team gets a sabbatical every three years... must be nice :) 

Asked for a "dummy contract" and info around GDPR to which I sent security and privacy docs. 

Connecting Wednesday to go through pricing more in-depth, and plan for next steps when he gets back from Indonesia.

1/31- Showed pricing, went through core use cases. Going to connect when he gets back from sabbatical 3/14. Already have some executive alignment which is positive.

column68: 3/12- sync after convo with Michael at Osmind.
column71:
-Shanna is Director of PM at Creative Force
-She is focusing on automating processes they’re doing manually today
-There are 3 PMs on her team who review insights in Productboard and its very manual
-Also, the person ingesting feedback isn’t the person who needs to do the deeper discovery on that feedback (basically discussing the gap between people who receive feedback directly from customers vs the actual product team who needs insights about this feedback)
-We were trying understand trends and optimizing experience, but volume has gotten too high and has created a gap in our understanding
-Primarily getting feedback through Intercom and Chorus, some surveys and emails

What decisions are you trying to make?
-OKR Framework to identify and justify what we’re gonna focus on our goals for the quarter
-For ex: might want to understand Product market fit for a new module they introduced - will need to see the feedback about that module, or maybe if its a feature that gets a lot of usage, they want to see what the feedback is their to identify the main issues, 
-Want to allow PMs to easily search through feedback easily and find the data that’s going to support what they’re looking into
And also identify where we can go for application polishing and forecasting

What’s the biggest challenge?
-Searchability in PB is really lacking
-Lots of manual association between linking feedback to the actual customer and health of the customer

-They have different add-on modules, planning, coopywriting, video etc, 
-This quarter we’re on some big initiatives across the planning module to release significant new screens
-When we release that, we want to see how the feedback is being received - we have some visibility through Mixpanel

-Volume is unclear, a few hundred make it into Productboard every month, but definitely not every ticket is sent to PB, unclear on total # support tickets,

1/18- Had a solid chat with Shanna. Feedback was positive from the product team, but "the proof will be in the pudding". 

The key thing here is she cares about depth of insights, and the PM team seems techincal. Key takeaway is eliminating the manual labor being 1.A, and feeling more confident in validating their hypothesis. 

Budget wise, there is budget to be had if we are able to check the boxes for her organization. Will continue to dig into this on 1/26. In the meantime, I've sent her and the team access to the Zoom playground instance, and will start adding sources soon.

Wants to add:
Intercom 
Chorus recordings...
Mixpanel may also make sense...

Manual process- KEY driver. Intercom full stop. 
Seeing feedback on new modules, releases etc would also be a key use case.
Proactive reporting of new modules. Sharing feedback on this internally.
"What are you going into product board for today?"

For V1, this is the use case. Talking a lot about journey from v1-v2-v3. 

Starting to analyze calls on chatGPT

3/5- Met with Shanna- this is going to be a tough deal to get over the finish line. Concerns about manual effort of the taxonomy primarily or the "formatting errors" so to speak, and getting it to a usable place.

Going to connect her with Osmind to see what she thinks after talking directly to an existing customer who has gone through a migration from productboard.

She's been incredibly thoughtful for a 12k deal, but appreciate her thoughtfulness. 

This is truly 50/50, connecting next week to see where things sit.
column72:
Taking into consideration current state Enterpret functionality, change management / operational processes, and cost as it compares to Productboard, Enterpret is not currently something we can move forward with at this time.


Your product has a lot of potential and I am excited to see how it continues to develop in the future, but unfortunately it is not the right fit for our operation at this moment in time.

User: Jack Divita Running into some issues with the % charts on the dashboard. Upon being filtered down on the dashboard, the % calculation is still based off the total number of unfiltered records as opposed to the total number of filtered records. The only way I can get it to properly calculate a filtered percentage was after I toggled “Measure as” from % to # to % again.

User: I’ll take this opportunity to also plead my case for one or both of the following:
• adding the count (#) to at least the tooltip when hovering over a bar on a % chart (especially in the dashboard view)
• Adding the ability to toggle between # and % in the ( ⠇) chart menu, similar to “Switch to Table View”
It can be much easier to parse/summarize results when looking at relative %’s (esp when comparing filtered results). However, it can be dangerous because of the law of small numbers, as the sample size for each percentage breakdown is not available at a glance.

Agent: > The only way I can get it to properly calculate a filtered percentage was after I toggled “Measure as” from % to # to % again.

> • adding the count (#) to at least the tooltip when hovering over a bar on a % chart (especially in the dashboard view)

Agent: Every record (feedback, user, or account) in Enterpret needs a unique identifier. In this case, we are asking for an id that can tell us whether a row is new or existing. This id can be anything – e.g., if you were using an export of data from Salesforce, you might use ContactId as the identifier for users.

User: sorry not totally following -- the instructions in census for selecting a sync key say that the column and field should have the same unique value -- so I was assuming somewhere in enterpret there is an ID field created for each record that is defined as their email

Agent: You're correct – when the sync ran for the first time and these rows were added to the User table in Enterpret, each one had its Id field populated with the user email

User: might be worth discussing live - it seems that for census to sync a record to enterpret there has to be a match on our source email and enterpret Id, and I'm not familiar with what the enterpret ID is or how it's defined (it obviously matches our source email or no records would sync)

User: sorry I think I get it now -- my first sync was an update or create -- so those emails didn't map to any id's but they were created during the first sync

column10:
User: Hi Jack Divita - We're rolling out a gen-ai support tool (forethought) and wondering if that's on your roadmap of data integrations. The plan is to rely less on routing feature request to discourse and handle them through AI-support chatbot as well as agent supported tickets. So in the future, we'd rely on zendesk and forethought for all of our feature requests received by support. cc: Chaitanya Hari and Marc Cruz who are starting to think about this on the support side.

User: cc Omar Guerrero

Agent: Its on the roadmap, though no timeline planned at this point. We have analyzed conversations handled by Forethought for quite a few of our other customers though
Interestingly, I have seen some inconsistency in the implementations. Do all of your Forethought conversations get sent to Zendesk or only the ones that get handed off to a human agent?

Agent: Additionally, in Figma's case specifically, which of these sets of tickets make their way into Snowflake?

User: only the forethought convos that get handed off to a human get sent to zendesk, interested in getting all forethought conversations into enterpret for analysis though

Agent: We need to figure out how to get that data out of Forethought then. Historically we have analyzed this data through a CSV extract that their reps have shared with us.
I will re-start the convo on our side, do you know if they are offering an API that would allow you to get all of your conversations into your instance of Snowflake?

User: they offer this as an out of the box integration, i'll ask them about what APIs they have available. We don't yet have forethought hooked up to anything

Agent: I suspect that will be the best route for us, given that you are sending us all of your Zendesk tickets through Snowflake and not from Zendesk directly
column11: The conversation discusses the integration of a new AI support tool, Forethought, into Enterpret Inc's system. The agent and user explore the possibility of sending all Forethought conversations to Zendesk for analysis and consider the use of APIs and out-of-the-box integrations. The conversation highlights the potential for improved data analysis and customer support through this integration.

column71:
-HackerRank's customers use their platform to conduct assessments with candidates, candidates will then provide feedback at the end of the assessment
-This feedback lives in MySQL (they are find with uploading data to Enterpret manually)
-This is the only source they seem to be concerned about
-They receive 7,000 pieces of feedback every week
-Way too manual to tag, want to identify bugs and prioritize feature requests
-They have a system for receiving alerts via email and slack if candidate provides low score, but sometimes candidates provide a high score but then negative feedback because they are afraid a bad score will affect their candidacy
-Sounds like they would also add metadata fields to the CSV before upload
-Early in their journey of identifying a solution, but want to make sure they find the right one, don't want to pick just any AI tool
column72: The main evaluator is junior and focussed on saving her own time, but there is not a broader consensus that this pain is worth investing money to address. They have shut down the evaluation because there are no funds available.

User: What is the easiest way to locate a specific ticket in Enterpret? I have the Zendesk link, and I tried running a search for the primary contact reason, limited by date -- no dice.

Agent: Hey Elliya - something like <<STRICT_LINK>> would work [essentially searching by the ID].
For tags, I think [Jack Divita can correct me here], Notion is not on mutable records, i.e., a notion zendesk ticket is only ingested once in Enterpret, normally after a short delay. Some tags are applied after ticket resolution, which is why searching on them wouldn't be reliable.

User: Ah, perfect! Thanks Arnav, that's exactly what I was looking for.

Agent: curious that the contact reason and date didnt work, was that just because it returned too many matches?

User: Hi Good Morning Enterpret Team!! cc Louise Sellars
We are in the process of sending more data into Enterpret, Feeld Social Media Messages. This new sync will take place daily. I have just run the sync from Census into Enterpret, please could someone help confirm this data is syncing into Enterpret.
Thanks :pray:

Agent: Hey Grant Orchard
Yes I can see the data flowing into the Enterpret (eg: Instagram Direct Messages, Comments, Twitter Direct Messages, Tweets, etc)
The feedbacks will appear on UI in 2-3 hours

User: Hi Hrishi, if I try to create a chart in quantify filtered down by social media platform I'm not getting any data, is this the right way to do it?

Agent: Hey Louise Sellars Grant Orchard
The feedbacks are ingested at around Jan 1970 because the `createdAt` field values are just year, but are required to be unix timestamps.
<<STRICT_LINK> to Quantify>
<<STRICT_LINK>>
Can the field values be fixed to have timestamp and re-synced? I’ve turned on mutability on our end, so we would ingest the updated feedbacks.

User: Thanks Hrishikesh Hiraskar I'll catch up with Grant on this one

User: Hi Hrishikesh Hiraskar a question from our data engineering team - do you need the unix epoch in seconds or milliseconds?

Agent: seconds :white_check_mark: :timer_clock:

User: hey Enterpret Team cc Louise Sellars Matt Miller - For Social Media Message data, which new webhook would best be suited for this data. I am setting up a new census destination. Account / Feedback or User?

Agent: If these are just messages from Social Media, they would be Feedbacks and should go under Feedback Integration

User: Hrishikesh Hiraskar Matt Miller cc Louise Sellars
I have built and tested the new sync from Census using the new webhook enterpret destination. This sync has sent <ZIP_CODE> records, thats 183 more records than yesterday. I see no error or failed requests can you confirm you can see the data flowing into your systems.
Also i needed to do a custom sql query for the message_sent_time = create_time :
```date_part(epoch_seconds, TO_TIMESTAMP(MESSAGE_SENT_TIME)) as message_sent_time,```

Agent: Hey Grant Orchard
I can see the feedbacks flowing in :white_check_mark:

column8: Channel, Keyword, Reason
column10:
User: Hey Matt Miller, do you know why there are no keywords or reasons on records from the `customer-research` slack channel?
<<STRICT_LINK>>

Agent: Duncan Stewart
• *Keywords:* In our current approach, we only do initial keyword tagging from user text, though we will subsequently highlight relevant terms in agent text. Since these are all internal messages, they are being considered as agent text. However, we are releasing an update to our keyword logic in a couple of weeks that should fix this.
• *Reasons:* It's not clear why reasons didn't get tagged here. There is one record that does have a few, and most of the rest have large numbers of suggested reasons, so it looks like the confidence just ended up being low in most of the cases. I am checking with the team to make sure nothing else is going on, though.
column11: The user inquired about the absence of keywords or reasons on records from the 'customer-research' slack channel. The agent explained that their current approach only includes initial keyword tagging from user text, with an upcoming update to improve this. The agent also mentioned that the low confidence in most cases might be the reason for the absence of tagged reasons.

User: hi Jack Divita Kayla Eliaza did we ingest some of our Forethought chat data via CSV previously? would it be possible to run an analysis on what are customers are asking the chatbot? CC Kylie Henson

Agent: We have ~130k forethought conversations from May 2023 through Jan 2024
We can definitely do this type of analysis!

User: thanks jack! that would be a huge help! would it be possible to create this analysis by Monday? sorry for the tight turnaround

Agent: oh

Agent: you didnt want it right now? :wink:
<<STRICT_LINK>>

Agent: ^ this is a good first draft - but since weve got a lot of time we can spend some time digging in and highlighting trends over time and specific quarters etc.
take a first look and let me know your thoughts - we can make it better tomorrow

User: amazing! thanks jack! we'll take a look and share our feedback

User: hey Jack Divita if we want to ingest more chats into enterpret, what would you need? is it just the chat id and transcript?

Agent: Almost, all we "need" is
• chat ID
• transcript
• date of conversation
Other metadata on who the user is is always useful. But what is typically most useful, is being able to do analysis that shows:
1. These are the tickets that the chatbot is good at solving on its own
2. These are the tickets that the chatbot had to pass along to a human
3. These are the tickets that only went to a human
it is not exactly clear to me how we separate the tickets into these buckets, is it safe to assume all of the tickets in 1) are the ones from the CSV? how do we know which ones are in 2)?

User: thanks! do you happen to know what the last chat date we previously uploaded? i'm also considering just taking feb onward. we turned off the buttons so this data would probably give us better info on what customers are asking
1. we don't have a good way for checking this now. the CSV will include all chats including escalated to a human
2. if the chat escalated to an agent, we'll have a ticket ID that i can add to it. however, a ticket is also created if the customer goes through the feature request, language intent, or the customer indicates at the end the bot resolved their issue. 
 a. there's also a deflect tag but this would also include dropoffs which could account for a majority of the chats

Agent: > do you happen to know what the last chat date we previously uploaded? i'm also considering just taking feb onward
we have through January end, so that makes sense

User: i'm working with Forethought to get the export. i'll share it over once i get it

column10:
User: Jack Divita Will Enterpret continue creating new reasons, ad infinitum? I'm going through and doing the work to merge similar ones, but curious if this will be a Sisyphean task :sweat_smile:

Agent: > Will Enterpret continue creating new reasons, ad infinitum?
Yes, we do refreshes every two weeks in order to capture insights from new product releases and trends from your users
> I'm going through and doing the work to merge similar ones, but curious if this will be a Sisyphean task :sweat_smile:
Nooooooo :sweat_smile: think of it more like weeding your garden than pushing your stone
You are correct in that technically the list will continue to grow over time, but I promise you that merging reasons together is incredibly high leverage to improve the quality of your instance. And we are actively investing in better tooling to learn from the types of merges you make, along with better automated deduplication

User: oh boy, I appreciate the reframe but it sure feels like pushing a stone right now :sweat_smile:

Agent: yeah, thats fair
I would be happy to help and/or hear your feedback on what is time consuming about it today - we want to make this process easier

User: 1. The wait time to see the changes reflected in the dashboard isn't great, since I feel like I still "see" the clutter while it processes on the backend. It's helpful that they turn grey!
2. The prediction of which reasons to merge is quite good! The search works well and having both the search and the prediction feels quite effective.
3. There are *so many* reasons that have only been applied to 1 ticket, and which have very subtle name differences. E.g. `Help Inviting Members` vs `Help Inviting Members in Notion` vs `Help Inviting Members in Notion Workspace`. Maybe for some products this would be a helpful distinction, but some concept in the model of "Everything is going to be part of Notion, or part of a Notion workspace. You do not need to differentiate between these concepts" could go a long way.
4. Sometimes the customers don't use the same words as we would to describe a feature. We get reasons with their wording, and with our wording. I've merged some of these to use our wording, but I have a feeling that more will keep popping up with the customers wording. Would be great to clearly indicate "these sorts of conversations are actually all about this concept -- label the reasons accordingly." Our clearest example is for a feature called `allowed email domains`, which lets users automatically join a Notion workspace as members. In tickets, this mostly shows up as complaints about "I tried to add <mailto:<EMAIL_ADDRESS>|<EMAIL_ADDRESS>> as a guest, but they popped into being a member! How do I fix it?" and the reason is called something like `Issue with unexpected guest adding behavior`. When I'm reviewing the dashboard, I need to understand that _our product is behaving properly_ and these are not bug reports. I've relabeled for now to be more like `Help understanding allowed email domain feature` since that's a category that will make more sense for our product teams

Agent: Elliya Cutler - thank you so much for this feedback!
Looping in a couple folks from my team to make sure this doesn't go to waste
Vivek Kaushal is our product manager and is designing our next generation of taxonomy (you should start to see some changes in Q2) - Vivek, let's make sure we are taking in to account Elliya's feedback
Ansup Babu is our machine learning lead working on reason deduplication. Ansup - can we run the new deduplication script on Notions data? I suspect it would be able to catch many of these examples provided by Elliya
Arnav Sharma is our CTO - FYI on some current pain points with managing the taxonomy

User: Running a dedupe script would be incredibly helpful! No rush :slightly_smiling_face: Appreciate you listening.

Agent: if we shared a spreadsheet offline sometime next week where you could go through and confirm/deny our automated suggested merges would that work?

User: sure! I was trusting/frustrated enough to just let you merge them :sweat_smile:

Agent: Hi Louise Sellars, here's what I think is happening: We tag keywords primarily from the user messages and not from the agent ones. In these examples that you mentioned (<<STRICT_LINK>>, <<STRICT_LINK>>) the entire conversation appears as a transcript within the agent message, and as a result the keyword detection is misfiring. I'm checking with the team to understand why our other inferencing methods (e.g., identifying keywords from reasons/summary) failed here.

Agent: Also relevant: we are releasing an update to keywords this month, and it should help resolve this issue.
column11: The user, Louise Sellars, faced an issue with Enterpret's Wisdom tool where some Zendesk ticket IDs related to 'Majestic' issues were not included in the export due to missing keywords. User: Hi Jack! Curious if it's possible for various Quantify modals on the same Dashboard to use different time ranges? E.g. If I want to see anomalous reasons on a 4W timescale, but continue seeing feedback sources on a 3M timescale. Seems like when I go to edit the filtering on one Quantify, it indicates that it has a "Dashboard filter" applied.

Agent: Yes this is doable, here is how
• create the individual quantifies on their own separate time ranges
• add them to the dashboard
• keep the dashboard time range as "default"
 ◦ If you change this time range at the dashboard level it will override the charts themselves
column11: The user inquired about the possibility of having different time ranges for various Quantify modals on the same Dashboard in Enterpret Inc. The agent confirmed that it is possible by creating individual quantifies on separate time ranges and keeping the dashboard time range as "default".

 Here’s a report on:

 :spiral_calendar_pad: Weekly Report: 25 March 2024 - 01 April 2024 
 :ballot_box_with_ballot: Feedback Count: 363 The feedback primarily revolves around issues with Feeld's Majestic features, chat functionality, and visibility of notifications. Users have reported problems with Majestic not activating post-purchase, persistent unread message notifications, and issues with chat functionality. Majestic Features Activation Issues Users have reported an *Issue With Majestic Not Activating* _(77 Records)_ , despite having purchased it. They faced issues with accessing Majestic features on Feeld, even after making the purchase and app reinstallation <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Persistent Unread Message Notifications Users have reported an *Issue With Lingering Unread Message Notification Dot* _(3 Records)_ . Chat Functionality Issues Users have reported an *Issue With Chat Functionality* _(27 Records)_ . They are facing issues with the messaging and chat feature of the Feeld app, with some users unable to send, type, or read messages <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Despite some issues being resolved <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> there are still reports of problems <<STRICT_LINK>]>. User: Hello :wave:,

 :spiral_calendar_pad: Weekly Report: 25 March 2024 - 01 April 2024 
 :ballot_box_with_ballot: Feedback Count: 248 Feedback on Feeld reveals significant user concerns about the presence of bots, fake profiles, and scams on the platform. Users also express dissatisfaction with the app's safety features and the handling of abuse reports. Concerns about Bots and Fake Profiles Users have reported an *Ability To Manage Bots* _(115 Records)_ , expressing dissatisfaction with the increase in bot and scammer profiles <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They suggest that the app is now filled with bots and fake profiles, which they suspect could be a strategy to boost the app's user numbers <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Users also reported an *Issue With Security And Safety Concerns In App* _(8 Records)_ , expressing deep concern about the safety features of the Feeld app, particularly in relation to the inability to block or disconnect from abusive users <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Scam and Fake Profile Concerns Users have reported an *Issue With Feeld Being A Scam* _(9 Records)_ , expressing concerns about potential scam attempts on the platform <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They also reported an *Issue With Scam And Fake Profiles On Feeld* _(3 Records)_ , encountering numerous fake scam profiles and warning against potential scams <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Issues with Photo Flagging and Fake Accounts Users have reported an *Issue With Photo Being Flagged* _(3 Records)_ , with their photos being flagged as inappropriate and unable to be removed <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They also reported an *Issue With Fake Profile Using Stolen Photos* _(3 Records)_ , expressing serious concerns and requesting for better regulation of such profiles to ensure the safety of users <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Catfishing and Harassment Concerns Users have reported an *Issue With Catfishing On Feeld* _(2 Records)_ , with one user having a negative experience where they were catfished and had their data stolen <<STRICT_LINK>]>. column9: Ability To Track Sentiment
column10:
User: hi Jack Divita i was wondering if it was possible to measure the sentiment change within a ticket. for example, does a customer start with negative sentiment but has positive sentiment at the end of a ticket

User: Do we ask for CSAT multiple times within a ticket’s lifecycle? I thought we only ask it when the ticket is closed.

User: nope, we only ask for the CSAT 24 hours after the ticket is solved (for email). twitter tickets will receive the CSAT every time the ticket is solved but we can adjust as needed

User: Nice! Is what enterpret calls “sentiment” different from CSAT? I thought they were the same 

User: i was looking at the customer sentiment throughout the entire ticket, not their CSAT survey. the thought behind this one is that we'd be able to find tickets tickets where the support team turned the customer's interaction around

User: Right. So what Enterpret calls “sentiment” is different from CSAT?

User: Jack Divita please correct me on this but Enterpret User Sentiment analyzes the customer sentiment through the ticket/interaction. "Satisfaction Rating" will be the customer's response to the CSAT survey

Agent: > please correct me on this but Enterpret User Sentiment analyzes the customer sentiment through the ticket/interaction. "Satisfaction Rating" will be the customer's response to the CSAT survey
This is exactly correct

User: thanks Jack Divita! do you know if it would also be possible to track the sentiment change within an interaction?

Agent: currently not possible, but this is not the first time we have heard this request. Have raised it with the engineering team and there will be exploration on the feasibility in the coming weeks

User: thanks! if this gets added to the roadmap, can you let us know? this could be a useful metric for us

Agent: definitely!
Before being added to the roadmap we will likely have some follow up questions on use cases and specific examples. Any additional details/thoughts you can share on those would also be helpful

User: of course, no problem
• positive -> negative:
 ◦ does this lead to churn?
 ◦ are there policies that are causing this change ?
 ◦ these can also be used to identify coaching opportunities
• negative -> positive: 
 ◦ identify tickets where an agent did an good job. can be used to improve training or feedback for the agents

Agent: > • does this lead to churn?
This one is doable today without analyzing intra-ticket sentiment changes, we just need a little more data from Notion

Agent: Meaning - if you tell me which of your users churned (and when) I can tell you what problems they had before churning and how those compared vs users who have not churned
This is a VERY common use case today

User: In order to tell you which users have churned (and when), we'd probably have to pull subscription changes in from Stripe, which is managed by my team. Jack Divita, do you have any additional information about how/what you'd need from us to get churn data into Enterpret? I can ask my engineers if they have time for it.

Agent: The only thing I _need_ is something to join it agains the feedback record. For Zendesk it looks like we have user email, unique user ID, workspace ID, external user ID. For Gong we have workspace ID, user ID, and Email. For forethought, all I have is a record ID
I would also recommend including other additional metadata that might be useful for analysis: sign up date, churn date, churned ARR, number of seats churned, etc.
column11: The user inquired about measuring sentiment change within a ticket and its difference from CSAT in Enterpret. The agent clarified that Enterpret User Sentiment analyzes the customer sentiment through the ticket/interaction, while "Satisfaction Rating" is the customer's response to the CSAT survey. The user suggested tracking sentiment change as a useful metric, and the agent confirmed that it's a feasible feature that could be added to the roadmap. The conversation also discussed the possibility of tracking churn data, with the agent explaining the data needed for analysis.

Agent: Hey Fred Kang Toby Laforest - Varun told me that you are working on a project to analyze closed lost in order to try and identify feature requests that might influence more won deals. Mitch Louie shared with me an extract of closed-lost deals over the last 6 months that I uploaded to Enterpret and we can use to look at common requests (and to compare/contrast vs. deals that were won)
Here is a link to the first iteration of the dashboard to help with this. I added some filters to the charts to try and highlight reasons that (to me) seemed actionable: <<STRICT_LINK>>
A couple of highlights that stood out to me:
• The ability to search through contracts comes up in lost deals twice as often as won deals
• Redlining documents comes up 4X as often in lost deals
• Setting reminders for contracts comes up 8X as often in lost deals
• A clause library comes up 6X as often in lost deals
• OCR on contracts seems is also a common one on lost deals
I am imagining this as an iterative process where we can continue to drill in to some of these reasons to make them more specific and further filter the list so it is as useful for you as possible
I'm excited to help start with this process and keep going from here - let me know your thoughts!
column11: The agent shares a dashboard from Enterpret, analyzing reasons for lost deals. They highlight that the ability to search through contracts, redlining documents, setting reminders for contracts, a clause library, and OCR on contracts are common requests in lost deals. They propose an iterative process to drill down into these reasons for specificity and usefulness.

column10:
User: hi Jack Divita we're trying to build out more dashboards to provide an analysis of feature requests and bugs for our product team. do you have some time later this week to meet about the best way to set this up?

User: i've listed some times we'll be free
• thurs 9-10am or 2-2:30pm PST
• fri 10:30-11am or 1-1:30pm

Agent: just set some time up for thursday

Agent: we can do some prep async too - any additional detail on what you are looking for?

User: thanks! i'm also going to add Elliya Cutler and Kayla Eliaza to the call.
we have a customer feedback catelog which includes feature requests and bugs about different components in Notion. we'd like to use Enterpret to provide product teams with quantifiable insights and verbatim quotes into these to understand what's more important and impactful to our customers

User: Thanks Jeremy and Jack! More details:
• we're specifically looking to examine our tickets that are coming in from Zendesk that are type `bug` or `feature request` -- not interested in `general question, stripe action`, or `admin action`.
• we're also looking to blend our zendesk tickets with gong data, so we can see verbatim customer quotes from both places when looking at a specific contact reason.
• we have a list of ~200 specific descriptions of Notion product areas (a few examples: synced blocks, the "wiki" function, database sorting, page deletion...) and we'd love to map that on top of all of the data we have in enterpret. right now, our engineers use those tags to determine if a specific area of the product is becoming buggier than we have a tolerance for

Agent: amazing - we should be able to do all of this
> we have a list of ~200 specific descriptions of Notion product areas (a few examples: synced blocks, the "wiki" function, database sorting, page deletion...) and we'd love to map that on top of all of the data we have in enterpret.
would it be possible to share the list ahead of our session?

User: Sure! What's a good format for you?

Agent: whatever's easiest for you - notion/csv/gdoc/slack all work

User: Hello :wave:,
 
 Here’s a report on: 
 
 :mag: Saved Search: <<STRICT_LINK> | *Complaints*>
 :spiral_calendar_pad: Weekly Report: 04 March 2024 - 11 March 2024 
 :ballot_box_with_ballot: Feedback Count: 281 Feedback on Linear's 'issue' category reveals that users are experiencing difficulties with various integrations, uploading images, logging in, creating issues, and using filters. There are also concerns about the complexity of Jira and issues with the Linear app itself. Problems with Integrations Users have reported issues with connecting to GitHub <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> Slack <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> and Sentry <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. These problems range from syncing and setting up integrations to triggering them and creating new issues. There's also an *Issue With Importing From Jira* _(3 Records)_ , with users unable to add a new synchronized project or edit/change the Linear Team <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Difficulties Uploading Images There's a persistent *Issue With Uploading Images* _(4 Records)_ on Linear <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Despite the support team's follow-ups, the problem seems to persist even after refreshing the app. Login Issues Users have reported an *Issue With Login* _(3 Records)_ to Linear <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Despite attempts on both PC and mobile, and even after following suggested troubleshooting steps, users are unable to log in. Challenges Creating Issues Users have reported an *Issue With Creating Issues* _(3 Records)_ <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They face difficulties with the issue creation process using Slack and have to resort to the standalone Linear app to create features and bugs. Limitations with Filters Users have reported an *Issue With Filters* _(2 Records)_ <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They find limitations in filtering and configuring the board for different components and have difficulty with combined filters. Complexity of Jira Users have reported an *Issue With Jira Being Complex* _(2 Records)_ <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They find it inefficient in managing projects and access rights and express a preference for GitHub issues. Issues with Linear App Users have reported an *Issue With Linear App* _(3 Records)_ <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They face persistent problems with Linear despite refreshing the local database and not using any proxy or VPN. View Saved Search button

User: Hello :wave:,
 
 Here’s a report on: 
 
 :mag: Saved Search: <<STRICT_LINK> | *User Safety*>
 :spiral_calendar_pad: Weekly Report: 04 March 2024 - 11 March 2024 
 :ballot_box_with_ballot: Feedback Count: 159 The feedback for Feeld reveals concerns about the prevalence of fake accounts, bots, and spam, leading to safety and security issues. Users have also reported instances of harassment and flagged photos. Suggestions for improvement include better profile verification, improved app performance, and a feedback section for users to share their thoughts. Prevalence of Fake Accounts and Profiles Users have reported an *Issue With Fake Accounts And Profiles* _(34 Records)_ . They have experienced numerous fake profiles that cannot be filtered out <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> and encountered scam accounts requesting explicit content and videos <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Users suggest improved app performance and profile verification to address these issues <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Safety and Security Concerns Users have reported an *Issue With Security And Safety Concerns In App* _(3 Records)_ . They have expressed concerns about being charged for a subscription despite deleting their account due to safety concerns <<STRICT_LINK>]> and suggested that the app may have security issues and amateur programming <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Harassment and Flagged Photos Users have reported serious *Issue With Being Harassed By Other User* _(2 Records)_ . They have experienced harassment, potential blackmail, and threats of sharing their private images online <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Additionally, users have reported an *Issue With Photo Being Flagged* _(3 Records)_ and are unable to delete the flagged photos from the site <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Bots and Spam Accounts Users have reported an *Issue With Bots* _(6 Records)_ and an *Issue With Spam Accounts* _(2 Records)_ . They have expressed frustration over the prevalence of bots <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]> and dissatisfaction with the prevalence of spam accounts and spam messages <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Users suggest that Feeld should improve its process for removing bot and Spam Accounts <<STRICT_LINK>]> <<STRICT_LINK>]>. View Saved Search button

<<STRICT_LINK>>

column8: Feedback
column10:
User: Nitpicky on formatting: the citation numbers here are all the same, but each of these actuall ylink to a different feedback record. Using the same number makes it look like all data is coming from one single record (which I would be less likely to trust - I don't want to weight any one response by that much). It would be great if each unique record could have a unique citation number. So, here it would be [1], [2], [3], [4] etc. because each link is unique. And if one record is referenced multiple times, re-use that citation number. (Is this actually a bug?)

User: Here's the actual copy-pasted report in slack:
*Confusion Over Developer Mode Access Rights*
Users have reported various *Issue With Development Mode Access* _(6 Records)_ , including mistakenly granting access to the wrong user <<STRICT_LINK>]> being unable to give dev mode access to another user <<STRICT_LINK>]> and their developers losing access to the mode <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Some users' access level was not sufficient for the dev mode feature to work <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Even after the issue was resolved, users were unable to regain access to their previous full dev mode <<STRICT_LINK>]>.

Agent: This is very helpful feedback Molly Jane Nicholas, thank you for sharing!

User: I always thought the citation numbers represented counts of records :thinking_face: 

User: That would be a very non-standard usage of the citation format - if they're meant to represent counts I would strongly ask that they not use the standard citation format which pretty much universally means "specific link to single resource". Something like (_x records_) (the way it appears at the top) would work for counts.

User: Molly Jane Nicholas is this how ivy league presidents get fired? lol

User: Just coming back to this - it doesn't seem to mean counts: each number links to only one record. If it represents multiple records, it would need to link to each one.

User: Thanks Molly Jane Nicholas! definitely my oversight.

Agent: > each number links to only one record.
That’s correct Molly Jane Nicholas — just adding some more context on the current behaviour — the numbers start from 1 for each claim in a summary. E.g:
> Users appreciate Figma’s user interface [1][2], and visual design [1]. They also appreciate They also appreciate its robust prototyping tools [1][2][3].
For this sample from a summary, 2 specific records are cited where users have praised the user interface, 1 specific record where users have praised the visual design, and 3 specific records where users have appreciated the prototyping tool.
Thank you again for flagging how this can be confusing! Have shared this feedback with the wider team, we’ll work on making this more intuitive. :raised_hands<IP>skin-tone-4:
column11: The user suggests that each unique feedback record should have a unique citation number for better trust and understanding. The agent acknowledges the feedback and explains the current citation numbering system. The user also suggests a non-standard citation format for counts of records. The agent appreciates the feedback and promises to share it with the wider team for future improvements.

column21: Michael Bartimer, Matt Miller

column71:
What motivated you to reach out?

-Valerie joined last week
-One of her first projects is to improve the product feedback loop
-Feedback is not reliably making its way to the product team
-In terms of current process for making sure Product team has visibility into actionable insights, they have a complicated process where internal users will submit a ticket which then goes into Notion for CSMs to analyze, then they send it to Product who has has to piece meal it with the right segmentation, ARR, 
-Overall she does not like how much internal bias and analysis is being doing before making its way to product, would rather just have a strong automated analysis of raw feedback, product is still spending too much time analyzing feedback when they should just be making informed decisions

Sources
-Zendesk
-CS and Sales Calls and Emails - Gong and Salesforce
-NPS surveys - can’t remember name of tool but its not an integration we have
 

How do you prioritize/segment feedback?
-Rating, high medium, low of how much they would like to have a particular feature
-Mentioned ARR data plays into prioritization
-Doesn’t think they’re using Census


-Really wants to know how to close the loop in Enterpret
Her job is to make this whole process but she believes her CPO is against the use of any third party tooling to solve this
-Asked for send case studies and might want to try to get CPO on demo call
-Wants to do demo late next week, but is traveling and will need to coordinate over email, tentative invite for Friday in the meantime
-Found out about us cause she saw our Notion Case Study Feedback Loop about a year ago
-Wants something in place by end of April
column72: Thank you for meeting with us this week! The demo was immensely helpful in understanding what use cases Enterpret could solve for us. Unfortunately, Josh and I came to the conclusion that Enterpret is not the right solution for us at the moment. Our focus is mainly on product operations, particularly internal and external communication and prioritization. We were genuinely impressed with the product and will certainly keep you in mind for the future.

Agent: Tanner Hopkins Clint How is everything going with Enterpret? Do you want to jump on a call to run through any current projects where we can support?

User: Hey Matt! Thanks for checking in. We are still facing challenges with the admin needed to clean up reasons. A PM sent me a message yesterday about a reason that's still tracking new feedback records even though it's out of date. It's getting to the point where they are becoming turned off from the reports being sent to them because the reasons are off.
As we've talked about before, we don't have the administrative time to clean them up. :disappointed:

Agent: > a reason that's still tracking new feedback records even though it's out of date
Tanner Hopkins Can you share more about this?

User: Yeah, we have a reason associated with customers who want a mobile app. Well, we have a mobile app, but feedback is still getting assigned to it even though we have a mobile app.

Agent: Hi Tanner Hopkins, got it. Here is what is happening – the reason `Ability To Have A Mobile App` has a few different definitions that have wrongly been grouped together. I will clean this up and move the incorrect ones elsewhere. We are actually working on some automated approaches to detect issues like this, since it is emerging as an issue for many customers. cc Arnav Sharma

User: Thanks! Yeah, I know how to clean it up, but thinking more broadly, this is just one example of many reasons that are wrong/out of date that require a lot of time to maintain, as we've talked about before.

Agent: Yeah, makes sense. We feel your pain and are hoping to make the taxonomy management process a lot easier soon!

User: I love to hear that!

column10:
User: Hey Jack Divita and Enterpret team. Madison Kohls is making changes to our zendesk model upstream from Enterpret. Are there additional steps or changes you guys need to make to ensure it flows through the platform properly? Starting a :thread:

Agent: it depends
can you share more detail on the changes?

User: We appended new columns to the table we sync over to you all, nothing has been removed (they are more metadata columns)!

Agent: shouldnt be a problem on our end and ideally the data should just start flowing over naturally
The only tricky part would be if you want us to backfill the existing data we have already ingested with the new metadata or to only have it populated moving forward?

User: Backfilling would be great, i backfilled the table on our end so curious how that would work for you all

Agent: its doable, but I will need to get my engineering team involved. let me check back with them to see what might be needed to get this done
When did these changes go into effect? (asking with the real intention of checking to see what columns were added to confirm I am ingesting them)

User: I believe yesterday

Agent: whats a new column I should look for?

User: ticket_contact_reason_tag

Agent: hmmm I am not seeing any data with that present yet. But I think you haven't synced any data to us today yet either - I'll check back after the sync

Agent: Madison Kohls we have not ingested any new data with this additional metadata - because we have not ingested any new data since Feb 27
Checked with my eng team and we are actually getting an authorization error for `CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_TICKETS` could this be related to the change you made?

User: Let me flag this to those who supported my change

User: I can confirm the DBT job has been running successfully and materializing.
```00:03:50 3 of 3 OK created sql incremental model ENTERPRET_SHARED_DATA.public.customer_feedback_tickets_materialized [SUCCESS 721 in 75.89s]```
While not very familiar with enterpret UI, I don't see any error messages there either.
We can loop in DI if needed.

Agent: Is there anything that would have changed with the permissions or authentication in the last 2 days?

Agent: For reference, here is the article for how the integration works on our side
<<STRICT_LINK>>

User: I see, let me check the exposures

User: The table was recreated yesterday for the backfill, so it seems likely that some permission changed somehow

User: Hi <!subteam^S03M4F9LS9M> - I see the environment associated with Enterpret uses the now defunct ETL role. See <<STRICT_LINK>>. Could someone from DI please replace the role in the job if that is in fact the issue and also update the ownership of the tables in question?
*Urgency:* Medium

User: Hi Jack Divita, could you help me understand how I can find out the connection details (user, role, etc) from the UI?

User: Michael Wu do you happen to know how enterpret connection is set up?

User: it doesn’t let me edit the configuration i’m guessing you can only see it on creation?

User: I was expecting at least an enterpret user and a role in Snowflake but I can’t find any

User: on DI side the credentials are created here: <<STRICT_LINK>>
these credentials work on a separate reader account created here: <<STRICT_LINK>>
(and so if we’re to debug query history we’d have to see the query history from within the reader account)

User: ah got it, i’ll try there

Agent: > it doesn’t let me edit the configuration i’m guessing you can only see it on creation?
I believe this is the case as well.
I am looping a couple engineers from our side to help with this as well, ideally we would be able to update the credentials of the existing integrations (perhaps something we can do on our backend as needed :thinking_face: ) because I would want to avoid re-syncing the entire table
cc Ishita Mundhra Vivek Kaushal - can we help Figma correct/debug this

User: I can see the problem being not the auth (I can log in with the same credentials, and I see query history from today). But there’s only `customer_feedback_reviews`, not the other one, and that could be the problem.

Agent: we haven't seen any issues with `customer_feedback_reviews` just `CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_TICKETS`

User: This is fixed now!
The issue is that when a view is recreated, the grant to the reader account is not applied automatically, and there’s no way to automate that (future grants to shares are not allowed). So as long as we don’t manually recreate views, we’ll be good.

User: Note for DS would be to inform DI when a full-refresh is performed for enterpret tables. Thanks Peng Wang.

Agent: amazing - thank you all for your help! I will monitor from our side to see when we see the data flowing again

User: Yazad Khambata can we document this somewhere? So we can simply point data infra oncall to the few commands they need to run.

User: I will ping you privately

column10:
User: Jack Divita Vivek Kaushal Sending a little inspiration your way… I am testing out using ChatGPT(4) to analyze some old survey data. I uploaded the CSV with the prompt “Provide a summary for the most common things that are keeping people from remote recording today. Include counts when possible.” The response it gave me back was very much the sort of response I was expecting/desiring to get back when testing out the new “Wisdom” experience in Enterpret.

User: Here’s the response:
> The analysis of survey responses regarding what’s currently keeping people from remote recording today reveals a wide variety of reasons, with each unique reason mentioned by only one respondent, indicating a high degree of specificity and diversity in the barriers faced. Here are some insights based on the data:
> • **Unique Reasons**: There are 91 unique reasons mentioned for not recording remotely. Some of these include not having the function yet, procrastination, uncertainty about where to record, not being ready to coordinate with others, needing an easier solution, not having equipment, and just not getting around to creating content of this kind.
> • **Keyword Insights**: By analyzing the frequency of words used in the responses (after removing common stopwords), we find several key themes:
> ◦ **Need (16 mentions)**: A significant number of respondents indicate a need for something, possibly resources, information, or capabilities, that they currently lack.
> ◦ **Time and Preparation (24 mentions combined)**: Words like “yet” (14), “time” (10), “havent” (11), and “no” (8) suggest that issues related to timing, readiness, and availability of resources are common barriers.
> ◦ **Technical and Process Uncertainty (9 mentions of ‘how’)**: The frequency of the word “how” suggests that uncertainty about the process or technical aspects of remote recording is a barrier for some.
> ◦ **Procrastination and Motivation**: The mention of “procrastinating” as a reason, along with the implicit suggestion of delay in words like “yet” and “havent,” points to procrastination or a lack of motivation as factors.
> 
> These insights indicate a complex landscape of barriers to remote recording, including technical challenges, lack of resources, timing and readiness issues, and motivational factors. Each respondent appears to have a unique set of challenges, underscoring the need for tailored solutions to address these barriers.

Agent: Really appreciate the inspiration and the feedback here Mike McNasby :pray<IP>skin-tone-4:
CC Arnav Sharma (CTO)

Agent: Mike McNasby thanks for sharing!
Doing a quick comparison against Wisdom today, here was the response:
The analysis of user feedback reveals that the most common issues preventing users from remote recording on Descript are related to linking and using Squadcast, audio quality, logging into Squadcast, and uploading recordings.
• *Issues Linking and Using Squadcast with Descript*: Users have reported an *Issue With Linking Squadcast To Descript*(109 Records)<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]> and an *Issue With Recording With Squadcast*(46 Records)<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They have faced difficulties with the integration of Squadcast and Descript, such as the 'edit in Descript' feature<<STRICT_LINK>]> and issues with the SquadCast feature of Descript<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>.
• *Poor Audio Quality in Squadcast*: Users have reported an *Issue With Audio Quality In Squadcast*(34 Records) during remote recordings<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They have experienced audio issues, including weak connection, choppy video and audio, and syncing issues<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>. Users have also reported significant audio delay and frequent video freezing issues<<STRICT_LINK>]>.
• *Difficulties Logging into Squadcast*: Users have reported an *Issue With Logging Into Squadcast*(32 Records), which is a part of their Remote Recording setup<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They have faced trouble logging in, issues with linking their Descript and Squadcast accounts, and problems with logging in after deleting their Google account.
• *Troubles Uploading Recordings on Squadcast*: Users have reported an *Issue With Uploading Recordings On Squadcast*(16 Records)<<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>, <<STRICT_LINK>]>. They have faced trouble uploading local recordings on Descript for their SquadCast guests, issues with uploading a recording from Squadcast to Descript, and problems with video uploading, rendering time, lag, and poor audio quality.


Agent: Agreed - chat GPT did a better job of understanding the intention of the question revolved around `keeping people from remote recording today` but chatgpt wont give you the citations to see the quotes themselves

Agent: but even having the ciations in this case (i assume) is actually not as useful because we didn't quite understand the question correctly - we anchored on general complaints remote recording instead of focusing on what users said was preventing them from using it

User: Jack Divita Michael Nguyen Is there a definition for how Enterpret defines sentiment?

Agent: Hey Heath Rogers here is an overview of generally how sentiment is calculated on our platform
One thing I would like to note - personally I am not a huge fan of sentiment analysis. My view is that sentiment outputs tend to not be very actionable as far as understanding root causes, let alone potential solutions to customer problems - whereas the outputs of our `Reasons` are meant to be descriptive and actionable
I am curious what you are hoping to use the Sentiment reporting for? My guess is that we can do the same thing (and better) by using the output of some of our more descriptive models

column71:
2/26- Met with the Elena and Peter. Key sources:

Front
NPS/Survey responses (Survey Monkey/Delighted)
Intercom
Forums (Discourse)

First call was primarily around high level overview of Enterpret. Both of these folks are on the user research team. Peter is more focused on interveiws/community work, and Elena is more focused on the data piece. She's his data counterpart.

Spent the bulk of today's call talking about core use cases/what they're having issues with today. 

This is a bit less about product strategy, and more about having the right data/eliminating institutional knowledge.

"we know what the top 10/10 issues are, and how to work on those, but need more data around the 2s and 3s"

They work primarily with the self serve team, and there's not as much visibility into what that group needs/is asking for.

Talked about process today. There is something roughly in place for tickets as far as front goes, but they certainly miss some things in manually tagging. 

Asked about wanting to go through and measure impact, and segment out by new users vs power users etc. 

This is clearly not a top priority for the organization today- there is no budget, this team is proactively looking for solutions. Said competitors were quoting about a 3rd of the price we shared. 

Bottom line: this is not a great opp for a multitude of reasons. Going to connect on 3/12 to see when makes sense to potentially do a trial, but will need to continue to push on the pricing piece/getting others involved/internal priority.

column71:
-Andrea has been at company for two months, working closely with VP of Product
-Noticed that analysis of feedback is lacking
-Wants there to be one place where product and research can go to see feedback and quickly consume feedback that’s relevant to them, need to more organized and transparent with feedback management
-Not sure if we need something that is purely a customer feedback tool or something, or if they need an to end Product Management tool like Airfocus
-Entire team is in Notion right now for Product Management
-Need to be careful in deciding what we need right now because we don’t want to tool hop
-Looked at a few tools already
-Selfishly she wants something that automates the analysis and summarization of feedback, what are people saying, how many people are saying it, etc…
-Tried Kraftful, but said its very basic and she can basically already do the same stuff with ChatGPT
-Want to have analysis of feedback so when leadership asks why we’re building something, we can show them the feedback, the segmentation, etc...
-receiving feedback via surveys, her colleague Max has a VOC program where he’s doing user interviews, support, cs, every source is important (gong, typeform, Zendesk)
-no process for unifying or analyzing, feedback is randomly shared in slack
-want to look at feedback over the last three months and be able to say, What is it actually telling us? Where should we focus? Why should we focus on that and then be able to go back to the commercial team and say this is what we’re doing and why
-How do you want to segment feedback? By product teams, so probably keywords
-Want to quickly see what people are saying talk therapy for example
-Asking about the ability to close the loop with customers
-Her overall thoughts: insights in enterpret better are better than Airfocus, but also Airfocus is end-to-end PM tool, need to discuss internally about what type of tool they need right now
-VP of Product wasn’t aware of evaluation at the time of the call, her and Max wanted to do research first and let her know what the options are, pros and cons, etc
-Next step is more in depth demo

User: We're seeing a weird mismatch between our Zendesk tickets, and how Enterpret visualizes the tickets.
Specifically, on Zendesk we see a big spike in tickets on Feb 1 (see 2nd image), but through Enterpret, it looks like there's not a spike until Feb 7.
What could be driving that difference?
• Is there a 6-day lag in when Enterpret gets the tickets?
• If not, what else could be driving this difference?
• Does this only assess sentiment analysis on first contact, or does each subsequent contact get a sentiment analysis?
Would love your thoughts on this Jack Divita

User: Molly Jane Nicholas do you know if the zendesk tickets are looking at ticket creation date or ticket resolution date?

User: Laura Perea Heath Rogers Do either of you know the answer to the above?

User: Kait Schorr has been looking into the snowflake > Enterpret pipeline and might have a pov.

Agent: This delay wouldnt be coming from our side. That being said, at a glance I suspect the root cause is that you are sending us the close date as the created date

User: I'm looking into this more today, I'll focus on Zendesk differences! This is helpful

User: I'm going to put together a doc of my findings for both sources and hopefully we can find someone to own it long term so we don't have the ambiguity around troubleshooting. Feel free to send me any details or weirdness you're observing.

User: fwiw My hypothesis is the state in which entepret ingest the tickets is different from the state in which zendesk is reporting the ticket dates.

User: The state of the ticket itself? I think I remember someone (maybe you!) Mentioning that. I will investigate that angle as well

User: This is already helpful all! It does seem clear that it's related to the state, and not some weird issue with incorrectly tagging, so I'll communicate that back to the team.

User: Molly Jane Nicholas I don't know... that was one of my questions. Norman Lemke Can you work with Kait Schorr on this?

User: The mode dash should be by creation date Norman Lemke to confirm

User: So if Enterpret is indeed close date it would be nice to switch that to match Jack Divita Michael Nguyen

User: I would also be very interested in seeing "sentiment on creation date" and "sentiment of close date" to see if there was a change throughout the life cycle of the ticket

Agent: Kait Schorr when looking at the snowflake table there will be two date fields that are required by us for ingestion:
• *ERC_CREATED_AT:* The creation timestamp of the feedback.
• *ERC_ROW_CREATED_AT:* The creation timestamp of the row in the table; helps Enterpret track what data to ingest.
Can you confirm that on your side the *`ERC_CREATED_AT`* is being mapped to the created date of the ticket itself?
Here is the link to the full documentation of our Snowflake integration if that is helpful
<<STRICT_LINK>>

User: Yes, looking now

User: So `ERC_CREATED_AT` is actually using the `UPDATED_AT` date of the ticket

User: Also the Zendesk tickets are also being filtered by the *`FEEDBACK_PROHIBITED_DOMAINS` table*

Agent: Kait Schorr can we correct the dates? We can help run a backfill on our end. Also, is that the only filter on the table? 
Michael Nguyen do we still need the prohibited domains filter?
Would it be possible to connect love sometime this week? I’d want to make sure we are all on the same page and that any updates we make fully solve the problem, so that we are not still working through this a few weeks from now 

User: The filters I've found are these:
user_id is not null
ticket status in (closed, solved, hold)
user_facts domain not in prohibited domains

User: One thing to note is we are in the middle of pulling data for an Exec Review meeting tomorrow so unless it's a quick fix we should hold Michael Nguyen Jack Divita

User: + Madison Kohls Perhaps we can capture this request to change the `ERC_CREATED_AT` to be the date the ticket was created, not the `UPDATED_AT` date in your current doc of proposed changes to the query.

User: Michael Nguyen yup! This seems to be from a model built _downstream_ of the query I am proposing. It seems like regardless we need to change the field from updated_at to created_at in this downstream model.

User: Which query are you proposing changing Madison Kohls?

User: NVM, Norman Lemke sent it to me. We should definitely set up some time to align on this

User: Yes! let me find a time for us, Michael, and Norman so I can give better context :smile:

Agent: Hi everyone :wave: sharing an end of week recap as there are a lot of exciting things going on between Figma and Enterpret right now!
Ever since we integrated the Zendesk ticket data we have seen a dramatic increase in the interest in Enterpret from all of you Figmates! This week had really great training onboarding sessions with Heath Rogers (and folks from your team), and Madison Kohls as representation from the billing team.
For anyone else who might be interested in getting started with Enterpret I have included two links below that I think will be useful for you all. First is a 10 minute overview video that will cover all of the basics of what you need to know to get started, and second is my calendar link along with an open invitation for anyone at Figma who might want to ask some questions and have more of a guided onboarding:
Link to video overview of Enterpret: <<STRICT_LINK>>
Calendar link to schedule personalized product onboarding: <<STRICT_LINK>>
I also wanted to highlight some ongoing work from our team:
• Molly Jane Nicholas Has created some really amazing dashboards highlighting the feedback on the recent Dev Mode launch. There are also a number of subscriptions directly pushing summarized insights to some team-specific Slack channels - this is *exactly* how we recommend taking advantage of feedback during product launches:
 ◦ Have a home page where everyone can align on the same data + trends
 ◦ Automate pushing insights to Slack so that people can stay up to date on whats going on without having to run their own reports (allowing them to deep dive if they see something interesting)
 ◦ To checkout her dashboard follow this link here:
 ▪︎ <<STRICT_LINK>>
• There are some gaps in the Zendesk data that we are working through. All of the analysis you can do in Enterpret will be correct, but there is a chance it is not fully complete as we are not ingesting every single support ticket. You can follow along with the progress in the thread linked below:
 ◦ <<STRICT_LINK>>
• This week we launched the beta version of our chat interface called `Wisdom` - this will allow you to ask questions and learn from your customer feedback through normal natural language (as opposed to constructing a query through our UI)
 ◦ I have attached an example of what this type of interface looks like
 ◦ If you are interested in participating in the beta product launch please let me know and I will add you
If anyone has any questions or ideas please do not hesitate to reach out - we love to hear from you all!

Agent: Hey Kayla Eliaza Jeremy Bui great catching up today to talk through our users+accounts modeling available in Enterpret. Summarizing our call below:
tl;dr - you can sync user + account metadata to Enterpret to enable advanced reporting on customer feedback, for example:
• Understanding the revenue impact of different reasons for feedback
• Understanding root causes behind user churn
• Understanding major causes for friction in user onboarding+activation 
The easiest way to set this up is to start syncing this data to us through Census, the documentation for setting this up is included below. You can sync any type of metadata to us as a part of this sync, the most important part is that we have a primary key that we can use to join against your existing feedback data. From Zendesk we are receiving a variety of different ID's along with the user email but it sounds like the best one to use would be the Notion user ID - which we are receiving in two different formats (which I have highlighted in the example below) - these two fields seem to be populated on about 77% of Zendesk tickets we have received in the last 3 months

column10:
Agent: Michael Nguyen starting this thread to follow up on something we were chatting about the other day - I think we need a clear definition and owner of the snowflake tables that are currently being ingested into Enterpret.
1. We need clarity on what data is being analyzed, and, even more importantly, what data is not being analyzed
2. We need to know who to go to when we want to make changes to the data model
 a. From my conversation with the support team this week there are new dimensions of metadata that we would want to bring in
Currently there are two snowflake tables that are being brought in to Enterpret:
• `Snowflake CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_TICKETS`
 ◦ Database name: ENTERPRET_SHARED_DATA
 ◦ This is Zendesk data
• `Snowflake CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_REVIEWS` 
 ◦ Database name: ENTERPRET_SHARED_DATA
 ◦ Customer feedback reviews table name: CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_REVIEWS
 ◦ These are Asana feedback tickets (go/voc)
For both sources we are ingesting a value for `erc_id` which, best as I know, represents the unique ID for each record on the Figma side. Based on previous conversations, I know that we are not being sent every single record for each of these sources - but it is not clear what the criteria being used to determine what records are sent to us. Even if we do not change this definition, I think it will be very helpful for everyone involved if we can atleast share this definition
I have included some analysis from my side to help with this investigation, but ultimately we will need someone from the Figma data engineering team to own this. For the Zendesk ERC ID's, they appear to be sequential and make me think that you are sending us roughly 40% of tickets. The asana ticket ID's do not appear to be sequential.
Spreadsheet with extract of ticket ID's: <<STRICT_LINK>>
Who would be the right person to ask about this and to own this moving forward from the Figma team? Is there any other data I can provide from the Enterpret side to help with this?

User: Hey Jack! Thanks for putting this together. I will hop in and help figure this out, or at least hunt down an owner.

Agent: Amazing - thank you so much!
Please let me know if there is anything else I can do to help

User: thank you so much Kait Schorr This is gonna be a huge win for us! :pray<IP>skin-tone-3:

User: Looking into the Asana tickets (so `CUSTOMER_FEEDBACK_REVIEWS` and they aren't actually incremental, they are randomly generated unique numbers, so the gaps between the numbers doesn't signify missing tickets. the `erc_id` is indeed the task id number, though, and you can only see it when you're using asana in the browser (it's the last bit of the url)

Agent: Hi Mitch Louie Julia Bendix following up from our conversation on Monday with my proposed next steps for our partnership together
• Fine tune taxonomy for more granular and actionable outputs
 ◦ Now that the taxonomy is fully customizable I recommend we follow a thorough and systematic approach by tackling key areas one by one sequentially. I am happy to help put in work on this front to help guide, but I cannot be the one making the tactical decisions on reason definitions
 ▪︎ I will never know your business and your priorities as well as you all. Who would be best for me to work with on this front? Mitch Louie should this be me and you?
• Nail down core use cases
 ◦ Manjit Toor I want your monthly support summaries to be as automated as possible. Using this template should get you 90% of the way there, do you agree?
 ▪︎ <<STRICT_LINK>>
• Expand to more core use cases
 ◦ Julia Bendix I know there are other executive reports outside of monthly support tickets that you were hoping to be sharing. Can you share some examples of what those might be?
• Expand to decentralized insight production
 ◦ At our other customers we have seen VOC have a lot of success by sponsoring dedicated Enterpret training sessions with product, support, and operations stakeholders (anyone who might have some use for customer feedback in their day to day). We spend 45 minutes together and by the end of it people know how to create their own reports and find their own insights
 ◦ I think we should be aiming to start running sessions like these by late February/early March when we have spent some more time fine tuning the taxonomy
 ▪︎ Julia Bendix How do you feel about that timeline? Any initial thoughts on who some of these teams who might benefit most from using feedback first hand would be?
