column71:
2/21- Had a call with Katy. Program Manager for scaled GTM. Paul had initially reached out to Julian, (Scaled GTM guy) who is looking for a new survey solution and suggested Katy connect with us.

Been on his team for 4-5 months now. Julian has PMM background, but now runs the scaled group. 

Two core use cases:
1- For scaled customers under a certain spend threshold, "how do we move them upstream?" 
2- Also responsible for overall VoC program across all accounts. 

Want to centralize feedback from NPS and CSAT Surveys. CSM feedback etc. Centralize it all, because the current state is "pretty immature". Collecting the feedback but it's not being utilized. 

Collected in a google sheet, or NPS responses are being sent to an inbox that you can read through 1 by 1. Don't have a place where all surveys are, so has to be pulled manually once a quarter. Looking to democratize this to:
- Improve decision making
- Reduce churn. 

Want to have an individual user be able to onboard better when they hop in. How do we help them to adopt.

Sources:
NPS - Gainsight (where the core emailed ones are) they are deprecating this in August, new solution in place by July 1st
CSAT - is via Pendo (specific product related CSAT) would want to pull that in as well. 
Zendesk- "Post interaction surveys" 
Gong- Some CS feedback there today, but also google sheets, SFDC where things are getting logged. 

Really siloed today. Focus is NPS/CSAT for her, support is in their own world doing their own thing. Would entertain pulling in Zendesk and seeing what makes sense to pull in today. 

Thinking of this as phase 1 phase 2 "what is the basic thing we could get in place by 7/1" after we're for sure we don't have a gap in surveying customers. 

They do have Survey Monkey, and not concerned with no Gainsight since they're moving off. 

Closing the loop is a big part of the equation as well. What exists to give different personas visibility, how do folks get notified of anomalous activity. 

Could do the following:
1- Gainsight v looker
2- Survery moneky and then a tool like Enterpret
3- All in one with something like qualtrics to send out the surveys etc. 

Think about feedback in a more wholistic way.

Having some more demos/internal conversations, particularly with folks working with Zendesk etc. 

Use RedShift as well. 

Connecting 3/20 now for next steps feedback/initial pricing.

Suggested doing Zendesk integration, Gong integration, then maybe a CSV for surveys. Still some concerns as for trials they've done in the past having a ton of approvals... so CSV uploads across the board might be easier.

3/25- "Hi James, I am so sorry to cancel this. I am still chatting with procurement about our path forward, can I reach back out when I have more info?"

This is not a particularly strong opp. Primary point of contact is Katy Durkin katy.durkin@lattice.com.
column72: We decided to go with a solution that could also send the surveys. Nothing wrong with the eval process, I genuinely liked Enterpret. It was just not the right solution for us at this time.

column71:
-Michael is Direct of Product 
-Float is focused on SMB and Mid-market, been around 13 years, in growth mode, 4,500 customers
-Looking inward at how we’re capturing and prioritizing customer feedback
-Previously used Trello to capture feature requests, started using Canny but it’s not sticking and not valuable, we’re more strategic about feedback than just looking at most upvoted feature
-Want to understand segmentation, industry, and who’s requesting certain features
-Sources include Intercom, Gong, Slack community
-Don’t prioritize based on most requested feature, 
-Want to segment feedback, key persona is people planning warrior which is defined as professionals services, 1-1000 team members, usually a role in operations
-Did a self-serve trial with Kraftful, - wasn’t impressed, seemed similar to just copy and pasting feedback to ChatGPT
-Likes Figma slide, they’re having a problem with defining OKRs with product focused metrics
-Liked the co-occuring reasons 
-Liked demo a lot, said it solves a lot of the challenges they’re having with categorization 
-Not sure about volume (ballpark 100 Gong calls)

2/1- spoke with team after sharing numbers $20-$25k annually. Said the budget is a feasible, but it's a bit high compared to what they're spending today. 

Mentioned $10k for Gong with one rep... Told him no doubt we'd be able to work with him (case study or logo rights)

Going to test the following:
Intercom: ~1200 per month
G2: ~10 per month
Gong: ~85 calls per month
Slack: ~30-50 messages a month

Colin (data scientist) had some concerns around slack, and picking up on non feedback, or feedback within slack replys. Told him we should try and see.

Colin also had concerns around the Hubspot integration, essentially said they would need a firm date on this as there's a ton of data on closed lost reasons etc. Makes sense, and potentially something we can make a contractual commitment on if we end up being a good fit.

Talked about the "merging" and "marrying" of Gong/Slack and Intercom, considering their metadata is extremely rich in intercom. Need to see if this is potential synced users and accounts.

Agreed to a 10 day trial period, and agreed to start with Intercom, G2, Slack and Gong, and not pull in the metadata with Hubspot at this time. We may have to do that at the end to win this deal.

This is a very real opp, we will have to discount, but need to focus on technical fit.

Sent a slack invite and instructions to get started, created an instance, and they will add the sources before EOW. 

Connecting on 2/8 to go through success criteria/journey deck.

2/8- Solid call, seemed like sorting by user types etc and MRR was the key use case here, so pushed for Census.

Got notified that if they exported from Census, they would need to upgrade accordingly so they will not for the PoV.

Jack is going to manually put together user and accounts modeling. 

They've asked a TON of questions around taxonomy etc, so will continue to partner with them. Had some legit concerns, but quite frankly I'm glad we're addressing prior to getting started on a PoV. 

PoV kickoff 2/15

2/15- Solid pov kickoff. Really got to the core of what we do before our formal kickoff. Started 10 day trial period. 

Asked a ton of questions around a few things:
- confidence in the data- "If I share this internally, I need to be 100% confident things aren't being double counted etc". 
- Taxonomy manual work (how much time will be spent fine tuning).

Overall seemed positive. They are sharing with the extended team this afternoon, and we will reconnect next week.
column72: Talked about data accuracy, but truly this comes down to low volume, and the ability to get what they need manually at this time. Will be a good opportunity down the road when they have more volume than they know what to do with.

column10:
Agent: _*[Duncan from PropellerAero]*_ Thoughts and Feedback about his use of Enterpret and Taxonomy -
His journey as a Insight Consumer (PM) starts usually at Keywords -> Feedback Records -> Open in Search -> Scroll each feedback record cursorily -> Read through Summary. Post this he checks if the summary is relevant from his tribal knowledge, in many cases it is sparse insights that he is able to derive from this. Like <<STRICT_LINK>> he is sure that Issue with _*Ability To Export Data*_ and _*Need for Ground Control Points Assistance: Users are seeking Help With Ground Control Points 19*_ are not applicable in context of the Keyword here - Google Earth.
All in all he is very happy with the Summaries direction as it is efficient for him to read multiple summaries, and extract meaningful insights from that as opposed to rabbit holing in Quantify land. One nit that he had though was that feedback generally starts from X records, but quotes show a very lesser number of feedback records Y, as part of summary (where Y<<<<X). His expectation was that it'd be aggregate validated. (X/X)
His general user journey is Keywords -> Feedback Records -> Open in Search -> Scroll each feedback record cursorily -> Read through Summary. Post this, he nuances this as part of a Coda doc wherein he adds EG1, EG2, EG3 (examples of Summary quotes, or favorited Feedback records) in a doc and finalizes a breakdown doc, which can then be used by PMs/URs/Designers in his areas to pick up Discovery for. (SS attached)
For Taxonomy -
• Keywords are very useful, but there is a lot of keywords that are redundant or unusable due to being very broad in nature. There is no capability to hierarchically manage these.
• He was pretty gung-ho about Reasons initially, but found them to be too broad in many cases, even if granular reasons are present, they are not top of mind due to the attribution of records towards broader reasons being really up the pecking order.
• He had heard from the team on 'parent-child' relation of keywords and reasons as part of T3, wasn't sold on the idea, but when I took him through the broad idea of customisable nodes, which can have <<STRICT_LINK> to many relationship> , he mentioned he was excited about the direction as this might reduce the noise a lot.
• He would want this relationship to be auto-generated as Admin'ing the Taxonomy(clean-up, merges, creations) is something he hates as a PM and would ideally need AI to fill that gap.
• He commented that currently reasons and keywords operate in a standalone manner, but should be more contextual and mappable (again not by humans, but by AI)
• He also mentioned that each feedback record, shows a lot of incorrect predictions for Categories, even when he starts from a completely different keywords in place and this is misleading and erodes his trust on the tool. (SS attached)
I also updated him on Oracle and he was super excited for this, as , paraphrasing - "For me to uncover insights by querying in natural language and see just not text, but list of Feedback records, visualizations, summaries in a single chat like interface is the direction which seems the most intuitive to me. Post having the relationships as part of Taxonomy improvements, I'm assuming the models would have a lot more context about Keywords, Reasons and their own relationships"
He'd be happy to provide feedback from Alpha stages, if required.

Agent: This is awesome Saurabh Arora, thanks for sharing! Did we get any insights on who consumes Duncan’s Coda doc and why?
Was the call recorded by any chnce?

Agent: This is consumed downstream by User researchers, Designers for discovery 

Agent: Got it. Curious about why these researches/designers don’t feel the need to visit Enterpret to read feedback about what’s identified // read adjacent feedback.

Agent: There is an additional layer of product sense and investigation required by Duncan, post finalizing the items he hands over to the research teams
column11: The user, Duncan, is satisfied with Enterpret's summary feature as it allows him to extract meaningful insights efficiently. However, he suggests improvements in the feedback record count and the contextual mapping of reasons and keywords. He also expresses a dislike for managing the taxonomy and suggests AI automation for this task. Duncan's Coda doc, which contains feedback summaries, is consumed by downstream user researchers and designers for discovery, indicating a need for a more intuitive interface.

Agent: Brian Hendery sarah barnekow A little experiment I did this afternoon –
I pulled some of the user and account data from Intercom records that are in Enterpret, and set up a sample User / Account sync to see if it would yield any interesting insights. One thing that I found is that the top Improvement suggestions change quite a bit when weighted by account data, in this example by the number of seats (in other words, potential seat impact of an improvement). `Ability To Assign Tasks To Multiple People` jumps from 3rd to out in front by a wide margin, while the `Ability To Create Custom Fields` drops to the bottom. A number of reasons drop out of the top 10 completely, replaced by new ones. Here are the charts:
• <<STRICT_LINK> By Feedback Count>
• <<STRICT_LINK> By Potential Seat Impact>
If this kind of analysis might be interesting, we can discuss more tomorrow about setting it up via Census, with a proper recurring sync.
A number of our customers have decided to set this up, and many are already getting value out of it. And we have decided to postpone any discussion on this being a paid feature, and are opening up access for free to all customers for the foreseeable future.

2/7- Had a solid Call with Heather (CS) and Nitya (User research)
The team was just in San Juan pounding Mufungo, and had been discussing better ways to make the most out of their feedback. 

Sources used:
Zendesk (8-9k per month for a small team)
App Store (50 a week)
Playstore (50 a week)

Nitya talks about focusing on bridging the gap from support like Heather and Emma (who couldn't attend cause sick AF) and mentioned the survey Monkey piece. Said her and the org manually go through and make sense of the survey data on why folks churn or don't renew on the existing offers.

Key thing is they do have a process that works today. They do this all via google sheets by specific producsts, specifics games within specific products etc. 

Asked a lot of questions around the practical use cases with product, and I talked through the demo that way accordingly. Here is the discovery, here's development, here's delivery and here's post delivery. This resonated well.

Asked about how to talk to product about this, and how we compare to canny. Talked through analysis v management- also resonated.

Said they're a super small team, and lots of folks might be interested in this. Going to evangelize internally, sent recordings, and shared ball park pricing $50-$60k annually. 

Need to get some more buy in on what we're doing from other folks, including product, before we proceed with a PoV.

Going to connect 2/21 to see if we're ready to start a PoV, really comes down to how much pain the rest of the org is feeling.

-Rebecca is CSM, Cynthia is the GM of CX and told her to take the call
-asking about ability to send feedback out of Enterpret
-lots of feedback multiple sources, primary source is zendesk, support tags tickets and adds them to feature request board in Jira, 2000 feature requests in there
-Having difficulty getting PMs to add even the most heavily requested features to the roadmap as they’re just focused on the strategic roadmap

What do you think is stopping PM’s from looking at the feature request board?
-Supposed to have have 80%, 20% split on building new things vs enhancing existing things, very difficult for CX to get things over the line, even if we say $5M worth of clients are asking for this, they just say they already are allocating resources toward building other things

What do you think would allow to build a better case about why things should be prioritized?
-The more data the better, revenue behind feedback, # of accounts requesting something, # of customers at risk of churn
-Trying to do their own version of SUA but its very manual
-for example, we’ll look at the most commonly requested feature, manually sort through all the revenue that is associated with that feature request, but then we don’t even know if this feature request has the most revenue behind it because there’s so many other feature requests, and also this is just feedback from zendesk
-doing this in jira because PMs use jira and if we want to get them to consume these insights it needs to be in their language and in tools they use

-Sales is using Gong, but not everyone uses Gong, limited licenses
-would also be good to use enterpret to recruit beta users as that is something product requests from them

-biggest concern so far about Enterpret is that a lot of their high value customers provide feedback via Zoom calls that are not recorded on Gong, and these customers don’t really provide feedback via Zendesk

User: Question about importing users. Do we need to import all of our users or just the ones with feedback in Enterpret? If it's just the ones with feedback, how do we go about limiting the important based on that?

Agent: Hi Tanner Hopkins, there is not an automatic way to only import users who have feedback in Enterpret – the sync just brings in everything from whichever table you choose. If you were to try and limit the import, you would need to do something like the following:
1. Export feedback data from Enterpret and assemble a list of users
2. Filter your source table to include only users with a matching feedback record
3. Set up the data sync from the filtered source table to Enterpret

User: I guess I'd do #1 using Quantify?

Agent: Yes, that's correct
column11: The user inquires about the process of importing users with feedback in Enterpret. The agent clarifies that there is no automatic way to do this and suggests a manual process involving exporting feedback data, filtering the source table, and setting up a data sync. The user confirms that they can use Quantify for the first step of the process.

column71:
-PM for Ria App
-In charge of feedback and VOC, said its fun
-There’s multiple places along the funnel/flow where they ask for customer feedback
-Has a feedback river that gives other members visibility into feedback, wants to encourage more people at Ria to look at feedback
-Sometimes runs ML model on feedback to surface most important issues
-They’re able to translate all the feedback into English
-Running AI model to pull the most important things but the process is a bit manual
-He’s really promoting VOC at Ria, wants to get other people in the organization to look at feedback more and wants to incorporate more sources into his flow
-Much of this is flowing into their product analytics software so they can quantify and segment data
-Zendesk is a black box but this doesn’t seem like a major concern
-Most of their focus is requesting feedback after certain actions along the funnel - for example, when user cancels a transaction, user deletes an account, user completes a transaction, etc… (using in-house survey tool for this)
-Interested in Amplitude integration

What’s the biggest challenge?
-I don’t see any blockers… VOC has been growing, I want to encourage more people to look at feedback and to add more data points to make product decisions
-Want to make the right decisions that are supported by data
-He’s been receiving great feedback internally about how he’s managing feedback and he wants to speak with us to make it even better

-Really wants to understand pricing and doesn’t want to join more calls, he’ll send over volumes and agreed to 15 minute pricing convo but wants breakdown sent to him beforehand
column72: Max already has a good VOC process. No major pain. Took call because his boss shared the outbound email with him.

column9: Ability To View Feedback Records For Specific Reason
column10:
Agent: Great feedback from Matheson Kuo at Boll & Branch: it would be helpful to be able to see which feedback records are associated with a specific *reason definition*, the same way that you always can for a *reason*. Example: You are editing a reason and trying to decide if you should break out a definition into its own reason. Sometimes it's pretty obvious from the definition name, but, here, `issue with defective sheets` seems like a boundary call. Being able to see which records (of 1,907 total) are being included under this reason on account of that definition would help you decide.

Agent: I have struggled with this as well
For example, Apollo wanted us to stop predicting certain reasons on records that were determined by an automated/pre-select option, but it wasnt clear from the definitions why that particular reason was applied to the record or which one we should remove to fix it

column8: Feedback
column10:
User: One more thing. Are there best practices for how I can indicate if I've triaged a feedback record or not and show of view of just those I've not triaged yet? As I'm going through cases and cleaning them up, I don't want to have to go over the same one twice.

Agent: Hi Tanner Hopkins, there is not a purpose-built way to tag or mark records to indicate that you have gone over them. What I often do is visualize the data in a daily or weekly view (depending on other filters – whatever creates manageable chunks) and then at least I can track my triage or review that way.
That said, you could use the "Save Feedaback" button to mark feedback records once you have looked at them. That will give them orange highlighting in the view feedback pane, but you can't filter on saved/not saved.

User: Ok, thanks for the tip!
column11: The user inquired about best practices for indicating if they have triaged a feedback record in Enterpret Inc. The agent suggested visualizing the data in a daily or weekly view and using the "Save Feedback" button to mark records. The user appreciated the tip.

column10:
User: A few questions
1. When I try to "and" together two keyword searches I'm seeing results that only come from one term. I've anded together "annotation" and "dev mode" as two tracked keywords, but the results in the screenshot dont' mention "annotations" at all. Am I misunderstanding how to setup the logic here? (BTW this "and" isn't what I ultimately want, just noticed the funky behaviour). <<STRICT_LINK> dashboard.>
2. Is there a way to pin the AI-generated summary to a dashboard? I'm finding that I want to use the dashboard as an "overview" over a longer period of time, while the slack subscription is more like "the latest". For now, I've added the "top reasons" to the dashboard, but the text version is much nicer to read (imo).
3. Is there a way to give feedback or train AI summarizing the findings? For example, in this summary, 
 a. "They also find the decision to include it in all editor seats or offer it separately for a monthly fee to be unfavorable" is in the "Dissatisfaction with Dev Mode Accessibility" section, but it seems like it would make more sense in the "Concerns about Dev Mode Pricing" or the "Unhappiness with Decision to Charge for Dev Mode" sections (which should also maybe be combined into a single section).
4. Just noticed I can drag/drop widgets now!!!! Game-changer!!!!! SO happy about this update!!!!!

Agent: Hey Molly!
> Is there a way to pin the AI-generated summary to a dashboard? I’m finding that I want to use the dashboard as an “overview” over a longer period of time, while the slack subscription is more like “the latest”. For now, I’ve added the “top reasons” to the dashboard, but the text version is much nicer to read (imo).
There isn’t a way to pin a summary to a Dashboard today, but this is exactly how we’re thinking about the near future! Super-glad that you’re finding summaries helpful, and would want to add them to Dashboards. We’re actively scoping this out.
> When I try to “and” together two keyword searches I’m seeing results that only come from one term. I’ve anded together “annotation” and “dev mode” as two tracked keywords, but the results in the screenshot dont’ mention “annotations” at all. Am I misunderstanding how to setup the logic here? (BTW this “and” isn’t what I ultimately want, just noticed the funky behaviour)
The summary in the shared screenshot (image attached) and Search seems to talk about both dev-mode and annotations Molly, are you referring to the feedback cited from Discourse in this case?

Agent: > Is there a way to give feedback or train AI summarizing the findings? For example, in this summary,
> a. “They also find the decision to include it in all editor seats or offer it separately for a monthly fee to be unfavorable” is in the “Dissatisfaction with Dev Mode Accessibility” section, but it seems like it would make more sense in the “Concerns about Dev Mode Pricing” or the “Unhappiness with Decision to Charge for Dev Mode” sections (which should also maybe be combined into a single section).
This is very helpful, thank you for sharing Molly! Here’s a <<STRICT_LINK> loom> on another avenue to share feedback on summaries from within the product.
Training the AI based on shared feedback on summaries is not automated today, but we pay close attention to shared points for improvements to the model. Looking forward to your feedback!

Agent: > Just noticed I can drag/drop widgets now!!!! Game-changer!!!!! SO happy about this update!!!!!
Thank you!! Have shared this with the team. :orbit-love: :orbit-love:

User: > are you referring to the feedback cited from Discourse in this case?
Yeah the discourse doesn't seem to mention annotations at all, just dev mode, so trying to understand how it made it through the filter. I was expecting the filter to filter only feedback that matches the filter criteria. Is that not what the filters do?

The agent responds positively to the suggestions and promises to consider them for future updates.

column10:
Agent: Varun Sharma and I had a great call with Dina Mohammad-Laity from Feeld this morning, and I wanted to share the positive feedback with the team. We continue to earn their deep gratitude.
Feeld has been on a _journey_ trying to manage the huge volume of feedback records that have come in since the relaunch of their app. Enterpret, with mutable Zendesk tickets that update every 90 minutes, has allowed Feeld to get a realtime view of the biggest problems they face as they come in.
• :speaking_head_in_silhouette: "This is one of the single greatest tools that we've had at our disposal." <<STRICT_LINK>>
Their chief of staff has been using Enterpret very deeply, working tactically with the engineering team on bug triage, but also using it to report to the executive team.
• :speaking_head_in_silhouette: "The Enterpret charts are there every day." <<STRICT_LINK>>
column11: Feeld, a user of Enterpret Inc, appreciates the product for its ability to manage a high volume of feedback records in real-time. The product's features, including mutable Zendesk tickets that update every 90 minutes, have been instrumental in identifying and addressing the app's biggest problems. The chief of staff at Feeld considers Enterpret as one of their most valuable tools, using it for bug triage and reporting to the executive team.

column71:
-Sajan and Antony both on CX team
-Working on creating a more efficient process for their quantitative analysis of customer feedback
-Currently doing this with ChatGPT to categorize the data
-They have their own list of problem categories and want to know how often are these problems being voiced by customers and what are the themes within those
-Various solicited and unsolicited sources of feedback - in-app feedback, quarterly survey (Qualtrics), appstore, we listen to audio feedback after speaking to an agent (Mindful - phone and chat - no transcript)
-Lacking quantitative analysis of Mindful data (some of this data is also in BigQuery), 


What decisions are you trying to make? 
Three key areas - product, platform, and service


Biggest challenge?
-Super manual, not sustainable as we continue to grow

-They definitely seem to want to have control over the taxonomy
-They t ChatGPT that certain comments need to fall under certain categories so that they can somewhat automate some of this analysis
-Estimated 2-3k monthly feedback volume
